<h2>Understanding the Three Presets</h2>

<h3>Document Clean (recommended)</h3>
<p>
  Applies 2% histogram clipping (removes the darkest 2% and lightest 2% of pixels before stretching),
  moderate contrast (+60), and edge sharpening. Best for typed text, printed documents, answer sheets,
  and books. Produces a result indistinguishable from a mid-range flatbed scanner.
</p>

<h3>Soft Scan</h3>
<p>
  A gentler version — 1% clipping, lower contrast (+28), no sharpening. Best for handwritten notes
  or pencil drawings where you want to preserve fine detail and mid-tones. The output is cleaner
  than the original photo but retains a softer look.
</p>

<h3>Photocopy</h3>
<p>
  Aggressive 3.5% clipping and very high contrast (+120). Text becomes bold black and the background
  becomes pure white. Some fine details are lost. Good for documents that will be printed on a
  photocopier or faxed — where high contrast matters more than detail.
</p>

<h2>How the Scan Effect Works (Technical)</h2>

<p>The tool applies four steps using the HTML5 Canvas API:</p>

<ol>
  <li>
    <strong>Grayscale conversion</strong> — each pixel is converted using the standard luminance formula:
    <em>gray = 0.299 × R + 0.587 × G + 0.114 × B</em>.
    This removes colour cast without washing out detail.
  </li>
  <li>
    <strong>Auto-levels</strong> — the tool builds a histogram of all pixel values and identifies the
    black point and white point by clipping the top and bottom N% of the histogram.
    The remaining range is stretched to fill 0–255, making the background clean white and shadows very dark.
  </li>
  <li>
    <strong>Brightness and contrast adjustment</strong> — a contrast factor formula sharpens the
    tonal separation between text and paper.
  </li>
  <li>
    <strong>Unsharp mask</strong> (optional) — a 3×3 box blur creates a smoothed version of the image;
    the difference between the original and the blur is amplified and added back, making edges crisper.
  </li>
</ol>

<h2>Tips for a Better Result</h2>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Use diffuse light:</strong> Stand near a window with indirect sunlight, or use a ceiling light. Avoid harsh directional lamps that create shadows.</li>
  <li><strong>Shoot directly above:</strong> Hold your phone parallel to the page — even a slight angle creates perspective distortion and uneven focus.</li>
  <li><strong>Use a plain background:</strong> Place the document on a dark or contrasting surface so the edges are visible.</li>
  <li><strong>Avoid flash:</strong> Camera flash creates a bright centre spot and dark corners. Flash-off with ambient light gives much better results.</li>
  <li><strong>Try Background Clip 3–5%</strong> for photos taken under warm or artificial light — this aggressively whitens the background.</li>
</ul>

